Q30:
I've made some bigger changes to courses, but I am sharing two smaller pieces.

We discussed different learning styles in the pre-lab lecture for a laboratory course. During the lab, I explained an anticipated result for the control reactions to study electron transport to a student who was really struggling with understanding electron transport in general. I could see the student still had a confused look and asked which learning style he connected with during the lecture. Visual. "Aha. I've been explaining this wrong," I said. Let's draw out what happens. The student started drawing what would happen in each of his experiments perfectly and showing his drawings to teammates to explain.

At the beginning of every Genetics lecture, I list the learning objectives for the day. At the end of the lecture, I repeat the list with sub-bulleted examples that were discussed or problems worked during class that were relevant to each objective, so that students could see how class activities were mapped to the objective. I initially told students that those objectives represented what I wanted them to be able to do at the end of the section/course, but they didn't appreciate these until I told them that when writing an exam, I start with the objectives, write a question that addresses one or more objective; and that the exam is done when all objectives have been checked off the list. I told them to look at the verbs in the objectives to know what I would ask them to do on an exam. At that point, students were more interested in the objectives. It was a reminder to me to be more transparent in how the objectives drive the course material.

Q30: One activity I do when teaching meiosis, after students have reviewed and reenacted chromosome movement, is to have them diagram how the chromosome configuration of Down's syndrome occurs. I have them move to one or more other team's diagrams to discuss with them what is correct or not, returning to make changes in their own diagram as they begin to sort out the correct answer.  I ask a team with a mostly or completely correct answer to send me a picture of their diagram, which I project for the entire class to see, and ask the team to walk the class through their thought processes as they produced the diagram. This can bring in inclusivity (depending on the team I ask to explain), gets at higher order cognition, is active, and provides formative assessment.

Q29:
The best example is when an international student asked why answer A below was not the correct answer.
What is the correct order of the processes responsible for the production of a protein, starting from a gene?
A) replication; transcription; translation (67.2%) (46.1%)(47.2%)(33.7%)
B) transcription; translation (21.5%) (41.1%)(44.2%)(52.1%)
C) translation; transcription (1.6%) (1.9%)(2%)(3.6%)
D) replication; translation; transcription (8.2%) (9.9%)(5.8%) (8.7%)
E) RNA  DNA  Protein (1.3%) (0.8%)(0.8%)(1.9%)

Upon explaining why A was the incorrect answer and B was the correct answer, he made the connection. We had similar issues to questions like this one in the past. So, I asked where and when did he learn that replication is necessary for gene expression? He pointed to the classroom. At that instant, I realized we teach and asses replication, transcription and translation in the same day, in the same chapter of the text and in same exam. The student combined all the processes into one concept and one purpose because we taught it that way. Since then, we have separated when we teach and assess replication and gene expression, and the results were as we expected. The percentages after each answer are the various semester we have asked this question on the exam. The first percentage is when we realized the issue and the percentages thereafter are when we modified the class material.

Q29: One year tried a breakout session to have students analyze a figure from a paper related to the lecture content we had just covered. The initial prompt was too vague and students did not know how to approach the data they looked at - mostly blank stares and little discussion ensued. The following year, I staged it into a series of targeted questions about the figure, first leading them through identifying the axes on a graph, describing what they thought the output in the experiment was, and then stepping through each line of data one at a time, before finally asking them to draw a conclusion about the experimental line in question. They discussed each question in small groups and we reconvened before moving to the next question. This helped identify misconception in the understanding of the figure and experimental method and led to many follow up questions from students that made for a lively conversation. Q30: Each week, in my 200+ student course, I ask students to identify one thing that they struggled most with or found confusing.  They are then asked to research this topic (they may use any help available- books, internet, TAs, friends) and write up a short explanation in their own words, with accompanying diagrams, that could be used to teach their classmates the concept. This has worked very well to teach students several skills at once- reflecting on their own learning, self-efficacy in seeking out answers, and expressing their thoughts clearly in writing.  The exercise is optional and carries only 2 points per week, but about two-thirds of the students do it. They quickly realize that dealing with confusion promptly makes learning much easier.  An added benefit is that they can share their answers with their friends and use the assignment to review for exams.  Some students have told me that they like this method so much that they have started to use it for other classes and that it has helped them learn better.
Q29: I teach a course in which the students (mostly sophomores) learn to read and analyze research articles.  This is a challenge, as they have to get up to speed on a variety of fronts to be able to make sense of a paper, even if I choose the articles carefully.  One problem was that they often could not distinguish between claims and the evidence for those claims.  To help them with this, I changed a few things.  One was having them, in pairs, research and explain to the class how techniques used in the paper worked.  The second was having them read the introduction, but no further, to identify the questions addressed in the paper, then providing them with only the figures in the paper.  Working in groups they are asked to use the figure legends to understand the experimental design, and then examine the data and decide what they could conclude.  Finally, they are allowed to read the discussion. This helped them identify what evidence there was for each claim and to begin to see that the idea was to evaluate the evidence, not simply report what the authors had said.

Q29: A couple of years ago, for a general biology course for non-majors I replaced some very dry lecture classes on cell organelles with an exercise in which students conduct research on the organelles outside of class, complete a pre-class assignment that tests their general knowledge of the organelles, followed by a double elimination debate. Each team of 2-3 students argues that the organelle they picked is the most important organelle in the cell. This semester I had such a small class that I could only have three teams, with ten organelles to discuss. My solution was to have three rounds in which each team had to choose an organelle that was not previously selected. This format turned out to be more effective than any I've used in the past because only one team at a time waited passively for a debate to end, and all students had to learn details on all of the organelles in order to prepare.

Q30: I created a strip sequence to help students understand the endosymbiont theory. I simply cut up a diagram explain the two endosymbiosis events, so that in the end there was a cell with a nucleus, a cell with a nucleus + mitochondrion, and cell with a nucleus, miochondrion, and plastid. I colored the mitochondria purple and the plastids green. There was also a cyanobacterium (green) and a purple bacterium (purple). The set of images was completed by two plus signs and two equal signs. Students arrange the sequence and glue it down. I thought perhaps the color coding made things too easy, but I was surprised by how resistant they are to the idea that an animal-like cell came before a plant-like cell. Students routinely insist that they are missing some pictures or ignore the color coding and put the plant-like cell first. I follow the strip sequence with clicker questions about order of events. I find that students remember the theory MUCH better if they work it out for themselves. I used to just tell them the sequence, and almost every forgot it by test time. Now they can diagram it.

Q30: It is always challenging for students to think in terms of populations, rather than of individuals.  The population perspective is a vital component to understanding evolution.  I use a free software program that tracks changes in frequencies in a population over time, and graphically relates changing frequencies to population averages and rates of change.  After orienting them to the software, I give them a set of parameter to "model" and have them discuss how altering parameters affects the population as a whole.  Each student manipulates his/her own computer, so everyone has hands-on experience.  I then provide an in-depth case study with real data and have students critically deconstruct/explain that real population in small groups.
Q29: Clicker questions in large groups are useful for helping me assess where misconceptions are.  Often I can predict a typical wrong answer, and I always include these as options.  When the MAJORITY gets the question wrong (which happens on occasion), I sometimes get feedback from the students that I haven't taught the material well, or that I phrased the question in a confusing way.  In the class period following a particularly rough complaint, I brought in a clicker question about the purpose of clicker questions, which launched a discussion about my intent to "undo" misconceptions.  I think they bought in, more, afterward.  Or at least they seemed to read more carefully and discuss more animatedly with their neighbors about what the right answer might be before they entered their choices.

Q29: I have used problems for years, but have found that having a special additional set of problems, without answers, for the weekly recitations to be very useful. Students do the problems using IF-AT forms in small groups. This promotes discussion and prevents students from simply waiting to hear the TA's answers. A few questions are always included that do not have IF-AT answers, so that each group of students can come up with their own answer and then compare their answer with that of other groups, rather than relying on the TA or instructor to provide an answer.  This is intended to mimic how science is done -- you confirm your answers by getting others to repeat the experiments, not by consulting a superior authority.

Q29: How to assign modest credit to active learning and participation. On the one hand if all of the effort students put in to active learning doesn't earn them any participation points, they are less likely to buy in. On the other, if I collect written assignments I inevitably don't have the time to provide direct feedback to all of them, and students worry and nitpick to get more points or complain that active learning is just a fancy way of taking attendance. I've finally (4 years in!) arrived at a participation-based reward system that is not labor intensive and still provides enough incentive for students to try and to attend class. Adding open discussions of "what's in it for them" (including showing evidence from the literature that this enhances their learning, and talking about Bloom's and how active learning will help them get up the pyramid) has helped the students accept the active learning exercises.

Q25: your questions  generalizing about faculty in my department will be hard to interpret.  Some faculty may be interested in active learning and improving educational outcomes while most others may not. Q30: I developed and implemented an exercise for a Genetics class to gather and analyze parent-offspring height data to estimate heritability, then went over the results in the next class session.  (I've done this a couple of times now.)

Our new Biology students in our introductory course are required to meet for a 3rd session during the week for "Recitation."  Each week, I create 6 prompts for active learning activities that they can tackle in small groups (4-5 students).  The prompts cover writing skills, first year seminar topics, logic problems, data interpretation, group projects, and occasionally hands on science (such as working with microscopes).  We cover the actual learning objectives for the day with complete transparency about why each is relevant.

I allow each group to work at their own pace with the requirement that they complete 5 activities for full points and have an instructor "check-in" before they leave.  I offer up a bonus point to everyone in the group if they can hit all 6.  This allows those who are learning quickly to leave early while those who struggle are able to obtain extra attention.  This format does require the use of strong TAs who can "sign-off" on activities, monitor stations with equipment (like microscopes), and who can answer the occasional question.
Q29:
I teach a non-science majors course in environmental conservation.  We were covering the topic of human population and food security and I snagged an activity from a textbook that presented the carrying capacity for each country in a balance sheet format.  I thought challenging the students to work out the math on the balance sheet would be fun.  I was wrong.  It came across as busy work and everyone was bored and actually frustrated that the numbers didn't tally (not every country was represented).

I now open the same "lecture" instead by pulling up the world population counter from census.gov.  As people walk into class, I simply let them observe the numbers climbing in real time.  It naturally prompts dialogue and questions.  Scrolling down on the website and picking out different graphs is an excellent way to get everyone genuinely interested in the topic and to actually "teach" through dialogue instead of flipping through slides.
Q25: The Summer Institute is simply fantastic.  Several of my colleagues attended this past year and I can already see how members are changing up their teaching and assessment strategies.  Students also seem to be more satisfied based on semester end surveys.

Q30: I work with under-prepared freshmen in a summer bridge program. As part of an exercise to promote a growth mindset, we talk about how learning occurs, down to the molecular level. The next day, students work in groups to develop a skit that illustrates what goes on during long-term potentiation (molecular model for learning and memory). This is quite challenging for freshmen, but the students have a blast during the skit competition. The active learning activity breaks down barriers between students, and between the students and me. Students are more likely to talk with me, or ask and answer questions after the skits. (Wish I knew if the exercise improves student success. That would be scientific teaching.)
Q25: Partly because several faculty members from my unit attended the SI, we are changing the way that faculty teaching is assessed. In addition to student evaluations (that we tried to focus on student learning), we are doing two types of peer evaluation: 1) Senior faculty will be evaluated every other year, and junior faculty yearly, using a pretty standard teaching evaluation template. These evaluations will go to the college for promotion and tenure decisions, etc. 2) At the same time, faculty teaching will be assessed using a more rigorous template that focuses on active learning and evidence-based teaching. These evaluations will not be high-stakes, nor will they be used punitively; they will only be used to help receptive faculty improve their teaching.

Q30: On the first day of my Neurobiology class, I talk to the students about the structure of the olfactory system.  I get them to brainstorm how the system might respond to many different odors, and turn these into hypotheses (each cell has a different receptor type, each cell has several receptor types,one-receptor-one-odorant, etc., etc.)  They then work in groups to think about experiments they could do to test these hypotheses (assuming they had any technology they want -- label cells, knock out genes, etc.).  It gets them thinking about how a particular sensory system might work, and also understanding the process of science better -- not memorize and regurgitate!
Q29: The above approach took a while to figure out.  The first time I tried it, I tried to cram too much in, and didn't guide them enough in generating hypotheses -- tried to have them do it individually rather than brainstorming. The Summer Institute was crucial to my designing and implementing active learning within my classroom. To a number of questions I answered that I was implementing a particular approach of activity.  Having said that, it is a constantly evolving process. Some are more mature than others. I frequently create handouts for the students to work on during class and follow that with formative and sumative clicker quizzes. But in a class of 200 when I walk through the classroom I see many students not bothering to work on the handouts. This is not an uncommon experience.  I don't want to  make it punitive by collecting and grading everything. ( I also don't want all the additional associated work.)

Some sessions are better are at getting students engaged than others but they all take a lot of preparation  You have to be in it for the "long haul".

Q30: With colleagues:  the 3 of us that attended have met with the associate dean of sciences and we are doing three major things:  1) presenting teaching tidbits on National Active Learning Day (Oct 25) to faculty and students, 2) starting a teaching and learning circle with the associate dean (something the dean wanted to do independently but was getting zero traction before we came back), and 3) presenting a mini-workshop on scientific teaching and inclusive excellence as part of our Teaching Workshop in January (the main theme is inclusive excellence, and we asked to participate, which was a request received with delight by the organizing committee).  Also within my department I am trying to have meaningful conversations re scientific teaching whenever possible.  With students, I am much more likely to ditch powerpoint slides in favor of an activity, usually having students count off so that they are experiencing new groups within the new semester.  I have noticed that more minority students are participating in leadership roles when the group size is reduced, compared to when the entire class is asked to participate in a round table discussion.
Q29: I have always found teaching "scientific method" a dreadful experience, as students feel they "know" it and despite trying to make it "real", it has always been flat.  This year, I borrowed a technique from a colleague to get students into groups, and then hand out index cards with different aspects of the method on the cards.  Then students were asked to either move around to get "their" card in the typical sequence of scientific method, or  (some of them did instead) to move the cards around on the table together, discussing it as they went. I could then visit each group, and ask questions about how they arranged things, and then let them decide what might work better in an efficient and effective scientific method.  It was FUN.  They were animated.  They argued. They laughed (especially the ones that were physically embodying their cards and shuffling around each other).  Then when I wanted to talk about some of the glitches in the system (why for example we often restart experiments or rerun them), they were more creative and attentive. Such a small thing, and yet such a long lasting result (I hope).
Q25: The Summer Institute came highly recommended to me from people I met at other scientific teaching workshops (much smaller in scale, and more like meetings than workshop actually). However, I am so grateful that I went, and I learned so much.  I just thought you should know that someone who might have looked slightly disengaged (I was really not feeling well the entire time) was actually taking away so much, and is now a champion of the workshop.  It might be worth letting organizers and facilitators know that they should not take it personally if someone in their group seems "not hooked",  It might just be that they are really feeling poorly and they could be taking away MUCH more than can be imagined based on just their affect while at the SI.

Q25: I entered the Summer Institute at Boulder after teaching a large undergraduate class for the first time in my life. What I learned was extremely useful in my later teaching practices, although implementing change has been very slow. Time has been the biggest limiting factor, the other major hurdle was to convince my co-instructors to change their practices. We discussed these factors at the Summer Institute, but it's different when you actually experience them. Another alarming trend I've experienced is that a significant fraction of my colleagues think that we do teaching innovations just because they sound good and please the administration. I admit that not all the changes I implemented in my class work, but the cloud of "suspicion" does not encourage anyone to do anything new. The administration cares about big changes, such as flipping the whole class. In reality, just incorporating active learning once a week significantly improves student engagement without redesigning the whole class. But changes like this do not get rewarded despite that they are effective.

These papers were initially of poor quality, especially the discussion section, which lacked critical analysis.  Now, I used a scaffolded design so that students turn in an initial section and receive TA feedback, then do rubric-guided peer review, then have instructor feedback, then finally feedback from the on-campus writing center, then turn in a final edited copy, along with all intermediate copies.  The reports are of much higher quality now, and the students learn that professional writing is about multiple stages of editing.

Q29: During the Snowpocalypse of 2015, students were totally stressed, angry and hostile (unlike anything I’ve seen in 20 years). I now use MazeFire games from time to time in my classes, for pre-tests, to generate discussion, for review and exam prep and to spark some more active and peer-to-peer learning.  The students play additional maze games back in the dorm room (often with classmates).

Q25: Techniques to teach abstract thinking to biology students instead of techniques of how to get biological facts stuck in their memories need to be featured in the Summer Institute. I teach statistics to biology students, and I do not feel I have been successful in teaching skills of abstract thinking to a majority of students in the class, which is the most important part of math-related training. As quantitative skills have been identified as critical skills for biology students, the Summer Institute should have an emphasis on teaching techniques for abstract thinking. This is important for instructors in non-math biology areas as well - unless most instructors for biology students embrace the importance of abstract thinking, students will never take it seriously. We know this from the fact that not many K-12 teachers emphasize importance of math to their students as they themselves are not comfortable. Consequently, not many students coming into college do not have much of abstract thinking skills. Unless the Summer Institute changes in this way, I view the activity of the Summer Institute as trying to improve education only where it is easier. I know another instructor teaching statistics to biology students who participated in the Summer Institute and felt it was a waste of time.

Q29: I used to give weekly quizzes in lecture, which was a bit of a slog for both my students to take and me to grade. After participating in the summer institute, I realized I could do more with less by making the quizzes collaborative and only giving them at key transition times in the course. I now give a quiz using IF-AT forms after each lecture chunk of the class (typically 2 weeks) and before transitioning to either a case study or paper to work on. Students take the quiz individually (without the IF-AT form) and then as a team (with the IF-AT form) just as was demonstrated at the Institute. It has worked great for 2 semesters now! Less grading for me and more metacognition for them.
